<!-- ABOUT FOREST FIRE -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Forest Fires</h2>
  <p>
    A forest fire is an uncontrolled fire that spreads rapidly through vegetation.
    They may be caused naturally (like lightning) or through human activities such as campfires,
    burning waste, or discarded cigarette butts.
  </p>
  <p>
    India faces forest fires in Uttarakhand, Himachal Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh,
    Odisha, Maharashtra, and Northeastern states.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- CAUSES -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Causes of Forest Fires</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Lightning strikes.</li>
    <li>Extreme heat and drought conditions.</li>
    <li>Human negligence (cigarettes, campfires, fireworks).</li>
    <li>Burning agricultural residue near forests.</li>
    <li>Fallen power lines or electrical sparks.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- WARNING SIGNS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Warning Signs of a Forest Fire</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Smell of burning or smoke in the air.</li>
    <li>Dry leaves and vegetation catching fire easily.</li>
    <li>Orange glow in the distance.</li>
    <li>Crackling sound from burning wood.</li>
    <li>Animals fleeing from forest areas.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Before a Forest Fire</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Stay updated with IMD fire alerts.</li>
    <li>Avoid campfires or burning waste near forests.</li>
    <li>Keep surroundings clean of dry leaves.</li>
    <li>Create fire lines to stop spread (for forest communities).</li>
    <li>Carry a wet cloth or mask to avoid inhaling smoke.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DOs & DON'Ts -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Evacuate early if fire is approaching.</li>
    <li>Cover nose and mouth with a wet cloth.</li>
    <li>Move to open, non-vegetated areas.</li>
    <li>Help animals escape and avoid panic.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT burn leaves or garbage during dry seasons.</li>
    <li>Do NOT stay near forest edges during heat waves.</li>
    <li>Do NOT try to outrun fast-moving fires.</li>
    <li>Do NOT return until authorities announce safety.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- HELPING OTHERS -->
